    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "To the Editor,",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "We would like to thank Drs. Ece Salihoglu and Ziya Salihoglu for their interest in our article.2",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 95,
                    "end": 96,
                    "mention": "2",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "While not directly addressed in the paper, the CURE clinical study data used in this paper considers patient gas concentration alongside both ventilator pressure and volume. The four CURE pilot trial patients had FiO2 set to 40, 40, 55 and 65 with PaO2 measurements of 71, 84, 60 and 101 mmHg, respectively. The McREM trial data used for validation did not provide specific oxygenation results.3 However, each patient\u2019s initial P/F ratio is provided in Table 1 of the paper, and indicates FiO2 varied in typical ranges.3",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 394,
                    "end": 395,
                    "mention": "3",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                },
                {
                    "start": 519,
                    "end": 520,
                    "mention": "3",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "The model presented in our paper was designed for use in an upcoming clinical trial that aims to optimise mechanical ventilation care.1,4 The trial uses two steps to optimise oxygenation. Step 1 optimises alveolar recruitment by titrating PEEP to the point of minimum elastance. The model thus safely maximises oxygenation via mechanics without adjusting FiO2. Step 2 uses this foundation to titrate FiO2 to achieve patient SpO2 levels within 92-95%. This process minimises the risk of excessively high oxygen levels, so the broad range of patients with respiratory failure can be optimally treated dependent on their specific condition and response to ventilation.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 134,
                    "end": 135,
                    "mention": "1",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 136,
                    "end": 137,
                    "mention": "4",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                }
            ],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Thank you again for your time and interest.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "",
            "ref_spans": []
        }
    ],
